Because of this inherent harmony, most Brazilians would not argue that we rely "too much" on science, as we are a culture that aspires to modern development, education, and technological advancement. However, there is a recurring cultural sentiment that society’s preoccupation with material progress can sometimes lead to a neglect of the spiritual and moral values that underpin our strong sense of community and family. We tend to believe that life is incomplete without both. Given this moderate stance—where we deeply value scientific progress but feel that a purely materialistic world would lose its soul—our perspective sits near the middle.

