Brazilian culture is generally characterized by emotional expressiveness, the pursuit of personal happiness, and a focus on romantic compatibility. While many may still consider marriage the "ideal" setting for long-term commitment, the social stigma surrounding premarital sex has significantly diminished over the decades. In contemporary urban Brazil, intimate relationships are largely viewed as private matters between consenting partners. Because Brazilians tend to prioritize affective connection and mutual consent over strict adherence to formal moral codes, the prevailing view is one of widespread personal acceptance, sitting comfortably on the progressive side of the spectrum.

